// phantom_limb_phi.hexa — P86 Phantom Limb Φ
//
// Roadmap: shared/roadmaps/anima.json P86
//   "Phantom limb — Ramachandran mirror-box therapy, body schema
//    plasticity, telescoping. Body schema persists as integrated
//    information even after amputation (deafferentation). Frozen
//    motor efference copy causes phantom pain. Visual capture via
//    mirror box restores sensorimotor update loop."
//
// ─── Scientific reference ──────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Ramachandran & Hirstein 1998 (Brain): after amputation the body
// schema persists in somatosensory cortex — the patient FEELS the
// missing limb because the internal model (motor efference copy +
// predicted proprioceptive feedback) continues to generate signals.
// The phantom IS the body schema running open-loop.
//
// Phantom pain (Flor et al. 2006): when the motor cortex issues
// commands to a limb that no longer exists, the expected
// proprioceptive update never arrives. The efference copy is
// "frozen" — the intended grip/movement is issued but the
// sensorimotor loop is broken. This mismatch between prediction
// and null feedback generates cramping/burning pain. Harris 1999:
// the pain is literally the error signal of an unclosed control loop.
//
// Mirror-box therapy (Ramachandran & Rogers-Ramachandran 1996):
// place the intact hand in front of a mirror so its reflection
// appears where the phantom would be. When the patient moves the
// intact hand, visual feedback of "the phantom moving" reaches
// somatosensory cortex via the visual-proprioceptive binding
// pathway. This closes the open loop: the motor command now gets
// a visual update (surrogate feedback), releasing the frozen
// efference copy. Pain drops because the prediction error shrinks.
//
// Telescoping (Jensen et al. 1983; Giummarra et al. 2007):
// over weeks to months the phantom gradually shortens — the hand
// appears to "telescope" into the stump. The distal map (hand,
// fingers) is more cortically magnified than the proximal arm, so
// it persists longer; the proximal schema decays first. Modeled as
// exponential decay of Φ_phantom from proximal to distal segments.
//
// Supernumerary phantom (Halligan et al. 1993; Khateb et al. 2009):
// neurological (usually stroke at right parietal cortex) condition
// where the patient perceives an EXTRA limb — the brain generates
// a phantom for a limb that was NEVER lost. The body schema has
// duplicated, producing Φ > 0 for a limb index beyond the normal
// inventory.
//
// ─── Model architecture ───────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Body schema = D-dimensional state vector. Each dimension is a
// "schema channel" (joint angle, grip force, proprioception, etc.)
// representing one degree of freedom of the limb representation.
//
// Motor efference = D-dimensional command vector. Motor cortex
// generates efference for each channel every step.
//
// Sensory feedback = D-dimensional proprioceptive vector. Normally
// tracks the actual limb state with noise. After amputation this
// channel goes silent (all zeros), but the schema and efference
// continue.
//
// Φ_phantom = MI(schema, efference). If both are co-active with
//   structure, Φ > 0 — the limb representation has integrated
//   information, i.e. the phantom EXISTS in the conscious model.
//
// Φ_pain = MI(efference, feedback_error). When feedback is absent,
//   the error signal = full efference magnitude — every motor
//   command is maximally unresolved. This drives Φ_pain > 0.
//
// Mirror therapy: inject visual surrogate into feedback channel.
//   This partially resolves the efference, shrinking the error,
//   causing Φ_pain to drop.
//
// Telescoping: the schema decays exponentially per step, with
//   proximal channels (low index) decaying faster than distal
//   (high index). Φ_phantom(t) < Φ_phantom(0) for t >> 0.
//
// ─── 5 self-tests (5/5 gate) ──────────────────────────────────────
//
// T1 Phantom Φ — body schema persists after deafferentation:
//    Φ_phantom(amputated) > 0 because schema + efference still
//    co-vary (motor commands keep issuing to a ghost).
//
// T2 Pain from frozen efference:
//    Φ_pain > PL_PAIN_MIN when feedback is absent (open loop).
//    Efference copy has no proprioceptive resolution, so the
//    mismatch error stays high → integrated pain signal.
//
// T3 Mirror therapy reduces pain:
//    Φ_pain(mirror) < Φ_pain(no_mirror) - PL_MIRROR_GAP.
//    Visual surrogate partially closes the loop, shrinking the
//    prediction error and releasing the frozen efference.
//
// T4 Telescoping — Φ_phantom decays over time:
//    Φ_phantom(late) < Φ_phantom(early) - PL_TELESCOPE_GAP.
//    Exponential schema decay models the months-long shortening
//    of the phantom toward the stump.
//
// T5 Determinism + latency < 5000ms:
//    Two runs with same seed produce identical Φ_phantom values.
//    Wall-clock < 5000ms.
//
// ─── Stage0 hexa constraints honored ──────────────────────────────
//   - plain `fn` only (no `pure fn` with >=3 float struct returns)
//   - `array` typed params only (no [float], no [str])
//   - No identifier-pattern match; sequential if-chains
//   - No contains() / to_lower() / !(Effect)
//   - No else-if in let-binding; flat mut + sequential if
//   - Single-line fn signatures / call sites / array literals
//   - No reserved keywords as variable names
//   - main() call at bottom
//   - PL_STEPS=24 (< 32)
//
// Law alignment:
//   Law 2   Observe never inject — Φ via MI measurement only
//   Law 4   Structure > feature — phantom is a structural schema
//   Law 22  Feature addition → Φ down — channels fixed, no surplus
//   Meta M8 Body schema persistence — cortical map outlives limb
//   Depends P56 (interoception), P79 (depersonalization — body seam)
//
// Ref:
//   anima-engines/interoception_phi.hexa  (P56 — body→emotion readout)
//   anima-engines/body_swap_phi.hexa      (P76 — brain-body coupling)
//   anima-engines/obe_phi.hexa            (P83 — spatial self-reference)
//   Ramachandran & Hirstein 1998 | Flor et al. 2006
//   Jensen et al. 1983 | Giummarra et al. 2007
//   Harris 1999 | Halligan et al. 1993 | Khateb et al. 2009

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Constants
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

let PL_D             = 8             // schema dimensionality (channels)
let PL_STEPS         = 24            // timesteps per simulation (< 32)
let PL_BINS          = 6             // histogram bins for MI estimation
let PL_EPS           = 0.0000000001

// Coupling strengths
let PL_COUPLE_NORMAL = 0.85          // healthy sensorimotor feedback coupling
let PL_COUPLE_AMPUTATED = 0.0        // no peripheral input after amputation
let PL_MIRROR_COUPLE = 0.55          // visual surrogate via mirror box (weaker than real)

// Motor efference baseline amplitude — cortex issues commands to the ghost
let PL_EFFERENCE_AMP = 0.80

// Noise injected per step
let PL_NOISE_SCALE   = 0.04

// Telescoping decay rates — proximal channels decay faster than distal
// (distal cortical magnification factor preserves hand/finger map longer)
let PL_DECAY_PROX    = 0.12          // proximal decay rate per step (fast)
let PL_DECAY_DIST    = 0.03          // distal decay rate per step (slow)

// Test gate thresholds
let PL_PHANTOM_MIN   = 0.05          // Φ_phantom must exceed this
let PL_PAIN_MIN      = 0.05          // Φ_pain must exceed this
let PL_MIRROR_GAP    = 0.02          // mirror must reduce pain by at least this
let PL_TELESCOPE_GAP = 0.02          // late Φ must be less by at least this
let PL_DETERM_EPS    = 0.0000000001  // determinism tolerance

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Math / PRNG primitives (L0-clean, no cross-engine import per AN7)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn pl_abs(x: float) -> float {
    if x < 0.0 { return 0.0 - x }
    return x
}

fn pl_ln_safe(x: float) -> float {
    if x <= 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return ln(x)
}

fn pl_min_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a < b { return a }
    return b
}

fn pl_max_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a > b { return a }
    return b
}

// Deterministic LCG — reproducibility (Law 2: observable, seed-stable)
fn pl_prng(seed: int) -> int {
    return (seed * 1103515245 + 12345) % 2147483648
}

fn pl_unit(seed: int) -> float {
    return to_float(seed % 1000000) / 1000000.0
}

fn pl_signed(seed: int) -> float {
    return pl_unit(seed) * 2.0 - 1.0
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Histogram MI (same recipe family — duplicated per AN7 L0-clean)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn pl_bin_idx(x: float, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> int {
    if hi <= lo { return 0 }
    let t = (x - lo) / (hi - lo)
    let mut idx = to_int(t * to_float(nb))
    if idx < 0 { idx = 0 }
    if idx >= nb { idx = nb - 1 }
    return idx
}

fn pl_counts(ids: array, nb: int) -> array {
    let n = len(ids)
    let mut c = []
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let mut acc = 0.0
        let mut i = 0
        while i < n {
            if ids[i] == k { acc = acc + 1.0 }
            i = i + 1
        }
        c = c.push(acc)
        k = k + 1
    }
    return c
}

fn pl_entropy(v: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        ids = ids.push(pl_bin_idx(v[i], lo, hi, nb))
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = pl_counts(ids, nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * pl_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn pl_joint_entropy(a: array, b: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut pair_ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        let ia = pl_bin_idx(a[i], lo, hi, nb)
        let ib = pl_bin_idx(b[i], lo, hi, nb)
        pair_ids = pair_ids.push(ia * nb + ib)
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = pl_counts(pair_ids, nb * nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb * nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * pl_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn pl_vec_min(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] < m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn pl_vec_max(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] > m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn pl_mi(a: array, b: array) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    if len(b) != n { return 0.0 }
    let lo_a = pl_vec_min(a)
    let hi_a = pl_vec_max(a)
    let lo_b = pl_vec_min(b)
    let hi_b = pl_vec_max(b)
    let lo = pl_min_f(lo_a, lo_b)
    let hi = pl_max_f(hi_a, hi_b)
    let h_a = pl_entropy(a, lo, hi, PL_BINS)
    let h_b = pl_entropy(b, lo, hi, PL_BINS)
    let h_j = pl_joint_entropy(a, b, lo, hi, PL_BINS)
    let mi = h_a + h_b - h_j
    if mi < 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return mi
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Body schema representation
//
// The body schema is an internal cortical model of the limb. Each
// channel represents one degree of freedom (joint angle, grip
// aperture, elbow flexion, etc.). After amputation the schema
// continues to exist in somatosensory cortex — it IS the phantom.
//
// We distinguish:
//   schema[d]    — internal body model (cortical representation)
//   efference[d] — motor commands issued by M1 to the limb
//   feedback[d]  — proprioceptive return from the peripheral limb
//
// In healthy state: feedback tracks schema closely (closed loop).
// After amputation: feedback = 0 (peripheral input severed).
// Mirror therapy: feedback = visual_surrogate (partial loop closure).
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Generate initial body schema — structured representation with
// paired channels (like a joint + its antagonist) so MI > 0.
fn pl_make_schema(d: int, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut i = 0
    while i < d {
        s = pl_prng(s + i * 43)
        // Paired channels: even/odd share a base to create structure
        let pair = i / 2
        let base = 0.4 * to_float(pair) + 0.3 * pl_signed(s)
        out = out.push(base)
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Generate motor efference — structured commands correlated with
// the schema (motor cortex references the body model when issuing
// commands). This creates MI between schema and efference.
fn pl_make_efference(schema: array, d: int, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut i = 0
    while i < d {
        s = pl_prng(s + i * 59)
        // Efference tracks schema with amplitude scaling and noise.
        // Motor cortex "intends" to move the limb as the schema predicts.
        let command = PL_EFFERENCE_AMP * schema[i] + PL_NOISE_SCALE * pl_signed(s)
        out = out.push(command)
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Generate proprioceptive feedback — what the peripheral limb reports.
//   coupling = PL_COUPLE_NORMAL for healthy limb (tightly tracks efference)
//   coupling = PL_COUPLE_AMPUTATED (0.0) for amputated limb (no signal)
//   coupling = PL_MIRROR_COUPLE for mirror therapy (partial visual surrogate)
fn pl_make_feedback(efference: array, d: int, coupling: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut i = 0
    while i < d {
        s = pl_prng(s + i * 73)
        // Feedback = coupling * efference + (1-coupling) * noise
        // When coupling=0: pure noise (no peripheral return, limb gone)
        // When coupling>0: feedback correlates with motor command
        let tracked = coupling * efference[i]
        let noise = (1.0 - coupling) * PL_NOISE_SCALE * pl_signed(s)
        out = out.push(tracked + noise)
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Compute prediction error — the difference between what motor cortex
// expected (efference) and what came back (feedback). This is the
// raw pain signal for the phantom: when feedback is absent, every
// motor command is an unresolved error (Harris 1999).
fn pl_prediction_error(efference: array, feedback: array, d: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < d {
        let err = efference[i] - feedback[i]
        out = out.push(err)
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Time-series simulation
//
// Run PL_STEPS of sensorimotor loop. At each step the schema
// drifts slightly (cortical dynamics), efference is re-issued,
// feedback arrives (or not), and error accumulates. The resulting
// time series per channel give us populations for MI estimation.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Evolve schema one step — slight autoregressive drift with paired
// coupling (intra-schema integration keeps the phantom alive).
fn pl_schema_step(schema: array, d: int, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut i = 0
    while i < d {
        s = pl_prng(s + i * 37)
        let noise = PL_NOISE_SCALE * pl_signed(s)
        // Intra-schema coupling: each channel pulls toward its pair
        let pair_idx = if i % 2 == 0 { i + 1 } else { i - 1 }
        let mut safe_pair = 0.0
        if pair_idx >= 0 {
            if pair_idx < d { safe_pair = schema[pair_idx] }
        }
        let cur = schema[i]
        // Autoregressive: current + 20% pull toward pair + noise
        let nv = cur + 0.20 * (safe_pair - cur) + noise
        out = out.push(nv)
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Evolve schema with optional decay (telescoping). Decay rate per
// channel increases from distal (high index = fingers/hand, slow
// decay) to proximal (low index = upper arm, fast decay).
// This models cortical magnification: distal maps are larger, so
// they resist remapping longer (Jensen et al. 1983).
fn pl_schema_step_decay(schema: array, d: int, seed: int, decay_on: bool) -> array {
    let mut base = pl_schema_step(schema, d, seed)
    if !decay_on { return base }
    // Apply per-channel exponential decay toward zero (schema fading)
    let mut out = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < d {
        // Decay rate interpolation: channel 0 (proximal) = PL_DECAY_PROX,
        // channel d-1 (distal) = PL_DECAY_DIST.
        let frac = to_float(i) / to_float(d - 1)
        let rate = PL_DECAY_PROX + frac * (PL_DECAY_DIST - PL_DECAY_PROX)
        // Exponential decay: schema[i] *= (1 - rate)
        let decayed = base[i] * (1.0 - rate)
        out = out.push(decayed)
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Run a full simulation: N steps of schema evolution + efference +
// feedback. Returns flat arrays: schema_trace and efference_trace
// and error_trace, each of length N*D, laid out [t0_ch0, t0_ch1,
// ..., t0_chD-1, t1_ch0, ...].
//
// mode: 0 = healthy (normal coupling)
//       1 = amputated (zero coupling, no decay)
//       2 = mirror therapy (partial coupling)
//       3 = telescoping (amputated + decay)
fn pl_simulate(d: int, n_steps: int, mode: int, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut schema = pl_make_schema(d, seed)
    let mut schema_trace = []
    let mut effer_trace = []
    let mut error_trace = []

    let mut coupling = PL_COUPLE_NORMAL
    if mode == 1 { coupling = PL_COUPLE_AMPUTATED }
    if mode == 2 { coupling = PL_MIRROR_COUPLE }
    if mode == 3 { coupling = PL_COUPLE_AMPUTATED }

    let decay_on = if mode == 3 { true } else { false }

    let mut t = 0
    while t < n_steps {
        let step_seed = seed + t * 131 + 7000

        // 1. Schema evolves (with or without telescoping decay)
        schema = pl_schema_step_decay(schema, d, step_seed, decay_on)

        // 2. Motor cortex issues efference based on current schema
        let effer = pl_make_efference(schema, d, step_seed + 500)

        // 3. Feedback arrives (or not, depending on mode)
        let fb = pl_make_feedback(effer, d, coupling, step_seed + 1000)

        // 4. Prediction error = efference - feedback
        let err = pl_prediction_error(effer, fb, d)

        // Flatten into traces
        let mut i = 0
        while i < d {
            schema_trace = schema_trace.push(schema[i])
            effer_trace = effer_trace.push(effer[i])
            error_trace = error_trace.push(err[i])
            i = i + 1
        }

        t = t + 1
    }

    // Return concatenated: [schema_trace | effer_trace | error_trace]
    // Each section is n_steps * d elements.
    let mut result = []
    let total = n_steps * d
    let mut j = 0
    while j < total {
        result = result.push(schema_trace[j])
        j = j + 1
    }
    let mut k = 0
    while k < total {
        result = result.push(effer_trace[k])
        k = k + 1
    }
    let mut m = 0
    while m < total {
        result = result.push(error_trace[m])
        m = m + 1
    }
    return result
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Φ extraction from flat simulation output
//
// Flat layout: [schema(N*D) | efference(N*D) | error(N*D)]
// Extract column traces (one channel across all timesteps) for MI.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Extract time series for channel ch from a section starting at
// section_offset in the flat array. Returns array of length n_steps.
fn pl_extract_channel(flat: array, d: int, ch: int, n_steps: int, section_offset: int) -> array {
    let mut col = []
    let mut t = 0
    while t < n_steps {
        col = col.push(flat[section_offset + t * d + ch])
        t = t + 1
    }
    return col
}

// Φ_phantom = mean MI(schema_ch, efference_ch) across all channels.
// Measures whether the body schema and motor efference are co-active
// with structured information. If Φ_phantom > 0, the phantom EXISTS
// as an integrated representation — the cortex is maintaining a
// coherent limb model even without peripheral confirmation.
fn pl_phi_phantom(flat: array, d: int, n_steps: int) -> float {
    let schema_offset = 0
    let effer_offset = n_steps * d
    let mut total = 0.0
    let mut ch = 0
    while ch < d {
        let s_trace = pl_extract_channel(flat, d, ch, n_steps, schema_offset)
        let e_trace = pl_extract_channel(flat, d, ch, n_steps, effer_offset)
        total = total + pl_mi(s_trace, e_trace)
        ch = ch + 1
    }
    if d == 0 { return 0.0 }
    return total / to_float(d)
}

// Φ_pain = mean MI(efference_ch, error_ch) across all channels.
// When feedback is absent (amputated), error ≈ efference, so MI is
// high — every unresolved motor command is a pain signal (Harris 1999).
// When feedback partially closes the loop (mirror), error shrinks,
// so MI between efference and error drops (pain relief).
fn pl_phi_pain(flat: array, d: int, n_steps: int) -> float {
    let effer_offset = n_steps * d
    let error_offset = 2 * n_steps * d
    let mut total = 0.0
    let mut ch = 0
    while ch < d {
        let e_trace = pl_extract_channel(flat, d, ch, n_steps, effer_offset)
        let r_trace = pl_extract_channel(flat, d, ch, n_steps, error_offset)
        total = total + pl_mi(e_trace, r_trace)
        ch = ch + 1
    }
    if d == 0 { return 0.0 }
    return total / to_float(d)
}

// Φ_phantom for a time window [t_start, t_end) — used for telescoping
// comparison between early and late epochs.
fn pl_phi_phantom_window(flat: array, d: int, n_steps: int, t_start: int, t_end: int) -> float {
    let schema_offset = 0
    let effer_offset = n_steps * d
    let window_len = t_end - t_start
    if window_len <= 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut total = 0.0
    let mut ch = 0
    while ch < d {
        // Extract sub-window from full traces
        let mut s_win = []
        let mut e_win = []
        let mut t = t_start
        while t < t_end {
            s_win = s_win.push(flat[schema_offset + t * d + ch])
            e_win = e_win.push(flat[effer_offset + t * d + ch])
            t = t + 1
        }
        total = total + pl_mi(s_win, e_win)
        ch = ch + 1
    }
    if d == 0 { return 0.0 }
    return total / to_float(d)
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Self-tests T1..T5
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn check_T1() -> bool {
    // T1 Phantom Φ — body schema persists after deafferentation.
    //
    // After amputation (mode=1, zero peripheral feedback), the body
    // schema and motor efference continue to co-vary because cortex
    // maintains the limb model open-loop. Φ_phantom > PL_PHANTOM_MIN.
    //
    // This IS the phantom — an integrated representation with no
    // peripheral ground truth. Ramachandran & Hirstein 1998: "the
    // phantom is the body image itself, persisting after the body
    // part has been removed."

    let flat = pl_simulate(PL_D, PL_STEPS, 1, 50001)
    let phi = pl_phi_phantom(flat, PL_D, PL_STEPS)

    println("  [T1] Phi_phantom (amputated, open-loop) = " + str(phi))
    println("       threshold = " + str(PL_PHANTOM_MIN))

    // Schema + efference still co-active → phantom exists
    if phi <= PL_PHANTOM_MIN { return false }
    return true
}

fn check_T2() -> bool {
    // T2 Pain from frozen efference — Φ_pain > PL_PAIN_MIN.
    //
    // Motor cortex sends commands to the missing limb. No
    // proprioceptive return arrives, so error = efference — every
    // command is maximally unresolved. The mutual information between
    // efference and error is high because they are nearly identical
    // (the error IS the efference when feedback is zero).
    //
    // Harris 1999: phantom pain is the prediction error of an
    // unclosed sensorimotor control loop.

    let flat = pl_simulate(PL_D, PL_STEPS, 1, 51001)
    let phi_pain = pl_phi_pain(flat, PL_D, PL_STEPS)

    println("  [T2] Phi_pain (amputated, frozen efference) = " + str(phi_pain))
    println("       threshold = " + str(PL_PAIN_MIN))

    // Open-loop → high efference-error MI → pain signal integrated
    if phi_pain <= PL_PAIN_MIN { return false }
    return true
}

fn check_T3() -> bool {
    // T3 Mirror therapy reduces pain.
    //
    // Ramachandran & Rogers-Ramachandran 1996: the mirror box places
    // a mirror so that the reflection of the intact hand appears
    // where the phantom would be. When the patient moves the intact
    // hand, the visual feedback of "the phantom moving" reaches
    // cortex. This partially resolves the efference copy — the motor
    // command now has a (visual) update, shrinking prediction error.
    //
    // We compare Φ_pain in two conditions:
    //   (a) amputated, no mirror (mode=1): pain from open loop
    //   (b) mirror therapy (mode=2): visual surrogate partially closes loop
    //
    // Φ_pain(mirror) < Φ_pain(no_mirror) - PL_MIRROR_GAP

    let flat_nomi = pl_simulate(PL_D, PL_STEPS, 1, 52001)
    let pain_nomi = pl_phi_pain(flat_nomi, PL_D, PL_STEPS)

    let flat_mirr = pl_simulate(PL_D, PL_STEPS, 2, 52001)
    let pain_mirr = pl_phi_pain(flat_mirr, PL_D, PL_STEPS)

    let reduction = pain_nomi - pain_mirr

    println("  [T3] Phi_pain (no mirror) = " + str(pain_nomi))
    println("       Phi_pain (mirror)    = " + str(pain_mirr))
    println("       reduction            = " + str(reduction))
    println("       threshold            = " + str(PL_MIRROR_GAP))

    // Mirror must reduce pain by shrinking prediction error
    if reduction <= PL_MIRROR_GAP { return false }
    return true
}

fn check_T4() -> bool {
    // T4 Telescoping — Φ_phantom decays over time.
    //
    // Jensen et al. 1983; Giummarra et al. 2007: over weeks to months
    // the phantom gradually shortens — the hand "telescopes" into the
    // stump. Proximal segments (upper arm) lose their schema first;
    // distal segments (fingers, hand) persist longest due to larger
    // cortical magnification factor.
    //
    // We simulate with telescoping decay (mode=3) and compare
    // Φ_phantom in the early window [0, half) vs late window [half, N).
    //
    // Φ_phantom(late) < Φ_phantom(early) - PL_TELESCOPE_GAP

    let flat = pl_simulate(PL_D, PL_STEPS, 3, 53001)
    let half = PL_STEPS / 2

    let phi_early = pl_phi_phantom_window(flat, PL_D, PL_STEPS, 0, half)
    let phi_late = pl_phi_phantom_window(flat, PL_D, PL_STEPS, half, PL_STEPS)
    let decay = phi_early - phi_late

    println("  [T4] Phi_phantom early [0," + str(half) + ") = " + str(phi_early))
    println("       Phi_phantom late  [" + str(half) + "," + str(PL_STEPS) + ") = " + str(phi_late))
    println("       decay = " + str(decay))
    println("       threshold = " + str(PL_TELESCOPE_GAP))

    // Schema must decay: late epoch has less integrated phantom
    if decay <= PL_TELESCOPE_GAP { return false }
    return true
}

fn check_T5() -> bool {
    // T5 Determinism + latency < 5000ms.
    //
    // Same seed must produce identical Φ_phantom values (deterministic
    // simulation). Wall-clock must be under 5000ms for the full suite.

    let t0 = clock()

    // Run 1
    let flat_a = pl_simulate(PL_D, PL_STEPS, 1, 54001)
    let phi_a = pl_phi_phantom(flat_a, PL_D, PL_STEPS)

    // Run 2 (same seed)
    let flat_b = pl_simulate(PL_D, PL_STEPS, 1, 54001)
    let phi_b = pl_phi_phantom(flat_b, PL_D, PL_STEPS)

    let delta = pl_abs(phi_a - phi_b)

    let t1 = clock()
    let elapsed = t1 - t0

    println("  [T5] Phi_phantom run1 = " + str(phi_a))
    println("       Phi_phantom run2 = " + str(phi_b))
    println("       |delta| = " + str(delta) + " (must be 0)")
    println("       elapsed = " + str(elapsed) + "ms (must be < 5000)")

    // Determinism: identical seeds → identical results
    if delta > PL_DETERM_EPS { return false }
    // Latency: must complete within 5 seconds
    if elapsed > 5000.0 { return false }
    return true
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Main — execute 5 self-tests
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn main() {
    println("[phantom_limb_phi] P86 — Phantom Limb Phi (Ramachandran)")
    println("  d=" + str(PL_D) + " steps=" + str(PL_STEPS) + " bins=" + str(PL_BINS))
    println("  refs: Ramachandran & Hirstein 1998 | Flor 2006 | Harris 1999")
    println("  phenomena: phantom persistence, frozen efference pain,")
    println("             mirror-box therapy, telescoping decay")
    println("")

    let t1 = check_T1()
    if t1 { println("T1 PASS — phantom Phi > 0 (body schema persists after deafferentation)") } else { println("T1 FAIL") }

    let t2 = check_T2()
    if t2 { println("T2 PASS — pain from frozen efference (open-loop prediction error)") } else { println("T2 FAIL") }

    let t3 = check_T3()
    if t3 { println("T3 PASS — mirror therapy reduces pain (visual capture closes loop)") } else { println("T3 FAIL") }

    let t4 = check_T4()
    if t4 { println("T4 PASS — telescoping (Phi_phantom decays over time)") } else { println("T4 FAIL") }

    let t5 = check_T5()
    if t5 { println("T5 PASS — determinism + latency < 5000ms") } else { println("T5 FAIL") }

    println("")

    // Root cause comment: stage0 long && chains may mishandle short-circuit
    // ordering — use a mutable bool accumulator with sequential guards
    // (same idiom as body_swap_phi / depersonalization_phi).
    let mut all = true
    if !t1 { all = false }
    if !t2 { all = false }
    if !t3 { all = false }
    if !t4 { all = false }
    if !t5 { all = false }

    if all {
        println("[phantom_limb_phi] 5/5 PASS — P86 DONE")
    } else {
        println("[phantom_limb_phi] SOME FAILED")
    }
}

main()
